With her calm focus, graceful movements and incredible stamina, Janja climb her way to the top of the world.

Born on March 12, 1999, in a small Slovenian town, Janja start climbing as an amateur when she was only seven. Even as a child, she canâ€™t resist to climb everything she see: trees, walls, even furnitures at home. Her parents quickly realised they had a natural-born climber on their hands. From the moment she leave the starting blocks, her determination and passion was unstoppable and her family and coaches always cheered her on, amazed by her focus and quiet strength.

At nine, Janja enter her first competition and won it. That early success push her to take on new challenges and stronger opponents. In 2015, she join the international circuit and begin to collect medals very fast. Her elegant climbing style, often describe as â€œdancing on the wallâ€, combine power, precision and intelligence. Soon, she become almost unbeatable.

Her list of victory is long: more than 49 World Cup wins and 10 World Championship medals, including eight golds, more than any other female climber in history. In 2019, she make history by winning every bouldering World Cup event in one season. At the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Games, she won the first Olympic gold medal in sport climbing. In 2024, she made history again by winning her second Olympic gold in Paris, becoming the most successful Slovenian athlete at the Summer Olympics.

In 2018, she competed less because of school, but still manage to win two golds and one silver, proving her discipline and balance between study and sport. At the end of 2019, she start working with coach Roman Krajnik, who help her improve her technique and mental strength before the Olympics.

Of course, such domination create envy. Some rivals cried foul at her perfection, saying no one could match her. But Janja always stay humble. She respect every opponent and believe that sport must be fair, a level playing field where everyone can shine. Besides competitions, Janja also loves climbing on natural rocks. In 2021, she became the first woman in the world to onsight a very difficult route graded 8c, one of the hardest levels in climbing. She keeps exploring new routes in Europe and pushing her own limits outdoors.

Today, Janja is a two-time Olympic champion and a role model for climbers everywhere. She is not only a champion, but also a symbol of progress for women in sport climbing. Her story prove that hard work and love for sport can take anyone to extraordinary heights. With her mix of talent, grace and humility, Janja Garnbret is truly on a par with the greatest athletes of our time, an unbeatable spirit who continue to rise, one climb at a time.
